This Master Services Agreement (MSA) is dated [DATE].
Parties
[FULL SUPPLIER NAME] incorporated and registered in England and Wales with company number [NUMBER] whose registered office is at [REGISTERED OFFICE ADDRESS] ([Lead] Supplier)
[FULL CUSTOMER NAME] incorporated and registered in England and Wales with company number [NUMBER] whose registered office is at [REGISTERED OFFICE ADDRESS]([Lead] Customer))
BACKGROUND
The [Lead] Supplier [and its Affiliates] [is OR are] in the business of providing [CATEGORY OF SERVICES].
The [Lead] Customer [and its Affiliates] want[s] to obtain and the [Lead] Supplier [and its Affiliates] want[s] to provide services on the terms set out in the MSA.
Agreed terms
Interpretation
The following definitions and rules of interpretation apply.
Definitions.

[Adoption Agreement: a written agreement substantially in the form of Schedule 2 that incorporates the terms of the MSA and is entered into by the Lead Supplier or one of its Affiliates and the Lead Customer or one of its Affiliates, creating a direct contractual relationship between them.]
[Adoption Date: has the meaning given to it in the Adoption Agreement.]
Affiliate: in relation to a party, any entity that directly or indirectly controls, is controlled by, or is under common control with that party [from time to time OR at the Effective Date].
Agreement: the MSA and any Statements of Work entered into under it [or, in the context of an Adoption Agreement, that Adoption Agreement and any Statements of Work entered into under it].
Applicable Laws: all applicable laws, statutes, regulations [and codes] from time to time in force.
Business Day: a day, other than a Saturday, Sunday or public holiday in England, when banks in London are open for business.
Business Hours: the period from [9.00 am to 5.00 pm] on any Business Day.
Charges: the fees payable for the Services, as described in each Statement of Work.

[Competitor: any business whose products or services are [directly] in competition with the Customer's [CUSTOMER'S PRODUCTS, SERVICES OR INDUSTRY OR THE RELEVANT PART THAT THE SUPPLIER WILL BE SUPPLYING] in the Territory, including [COMPETITOR NAMES].]

Confidential Information: all information (however recorded or preserved) that one party [or any of its Affiliates] (discloser) discloses or makes available to the other party [or any of its Affiliates] (recipient) in connection with this Agreement and which [is designated as confidential or] would be regarded as confidential by a reasonable business person. It includes the terms of this Agreement[, Customer Materials][, Customer Personal Data, Shared Personal Data] and any information of a confidential nature relating to the business, operations, plans, pricing, customers, suppliers, trade secrets, products, processes or know-how of the discloser [or any of its Affiliates]. It does not include information that:
is or becomes generally available to the public (other than as a result of the recipient's breach);
[can be shown by the recipient to have been known to it OR was available to the recipient] on a non-confidential basis before disclosure by the discloser;

was, is or becomes available to the recipient on a non-confidential basis from a person who, to the recipient's knowledge, is not bound by a confidentiality agreement with the discloser or otherwise prohibited from disclosing the information to the recipient;[ or]
[is developed by or for the recipient independently of the information disclosed by the discloser; or]
the parties agree in writing is not confidential or may be freely disclosed.
Contract Manager: a Supplier Contract Manager or Customer Contract Manager, as the case may be.
Contract Year: each 12-month period starting on the Effective Date or an anniversary of the Effective Date.

control: the beneficial ownership of more than 50% of the issued share capital of a company or the legal power to direct or cause the direction of the general management of the company, and controls, controlled and the expression change of control will be interpreted accordingly.
[Customer: the Lead Customer or an Affiliate of the Lead Customer (as the context requires).]
Customer Contract Manager: the Customer's principal point(s) of contact for managing this Agreement on behalf of the Customer appointed under clause 14.

Customer Equipment: any equipment, including tools, systems, cabling or facilities, provided by or on behalf of the Customer to the Supplier for use in the supply of the Services, including any items specified in a Statement of Work.
Customer Group Members: the Customer and each of its Affiliates, and Customer Group Member means any of them.

Customer Materials: all documents, information, [software,] items and materials in any form (whether owned by the Customer or a third party), which are provided by the Customer to the Supplier for the supply of the Services.
Customer Personal Data: any personal data which the Supplier processes under or in connection with this Agreement on behalf of the Customer.

Data Protection Laws: all Applicable Laws relating to the protection of personal data and the privacy of individuals, including the UK GDPR, the Data Protection Act 2018 and the Privacy and Electronic Communications Regulations 2003 (SI 2003/2426) [and the guidance issued by the Information Commissioner or any other relevant regulatory authority and applicable to the Services].

Deliverables: all documents, products[, designs][, software][, reports][, plans] and other materials or items [of any kind developed or provided by the Supplier as part of or in connection with the Services, including any deliverables specified in a Statement of Work OR to be provided by the Supplier to the Customer as specified in a Statement of Work].
Effective Date: [[DATE] OR the date that the MSA is signed by both parties OR the MSA Effective Date or the Adoption Date (as the context requires)].

Employment Regulations: the Transfer of Undertakings (Protection of Employment) Regulations 2006 (SI 2006/246) [and all other Applicable Laws in any applicable jurisdiction regulating the automatic transfer of employment on a service provision change].

Intellectual Property Rights: patents, [utility models,] rights to inventions, copyright and [neighbouring and] related rights, [moral rights,] trade marks [and service marks], business names and domain names, rights in get-up [and trade dress], goodwill and the right to sue for passing off [or unfair competition], rights in designs, [rights in computer software,] database rights, rights to use and protect the confidentiality of confidential information (including know-how [and trade secrets]), and all other intellectual property rights, in each case whether registered or unregistered and including all applications and rights to apply for renewals or extensions of, or to claim priority from, those rights and all similar or equivalent rights or forms of protection which subsist or will subsist now or in the future in any part of the world.
Key Personnel: the individuals identified as key personnel in a Statement of Work or any replacement individuals appointed by the Supplier pursuant to clause 8.

Losses: all liabilities, damages, losses (including loss of profits, loss of business, loss of reputation, loss of savings and loss of opportunity), fines, awards, expenses and costs (including all interest, penalties, legal costs (calculated on a full indemnity basis) and [reasonable] professional costs and expenses).
[MSA Effective Date: [[DATE] OR the date that the MSA is signed by both parties].]
Performance Date: a date by which an event, task or phase of the Services is to be completed, as set out in a Statement of Work [or agreed by the parties in writing from time to time].
[Policies: the business policies [and codes] [attached OR listed] in Schedule 3[, as updated from time to time by the Customer on notice to the Supplier].]
Regulator: each person having regulatory or supervisory authority over all or any part of this Agreement or [the Customer's OR any Customer Group Member's] business.

[Relevant Requirements: all Applicable Laws relating to the prevention of bribery and corruption, fraud, modern slavery and human trafficking and [OTHER], including the Bribery Act 2010, the Modern Slavery Act 2015 and the Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act 2023.]

Replacement Services: any services which are identical or substantially similar to any of the Services and which the Customer receives in substitution for any of the Services following the termination or expiry of this Agreement, whether those services are provided by the Customer internally or by any Replacement Supplier.
Replacement Supplier: any third party supplier of Replacement Services appointed by the Customer from time to time.
[Restricted Services: services which are the same as or [substantially] similar to the Services.]

Services: the services set out in each Statement of Work[, including all features, functions and responsibilities which are incidental or ancillary to those services or required for their proper and lawful performance].
[Service Credits: the amount(s) (if any) that the Supplier is obliged to pay to the Customer (or credit against the Charges) in respect of a failure to comply with a Service Level.]
[Service Levels: the service levels specified in a Statement of Work (if any).]
Shared Personal Data: has the meaning given in clause 16.3.
Statement of Work: a statement of work describing the Services to be provided by the Supplier and substantially in the form of Schedule 1.
[Supplier: the Lead Supplier or an Affiliate of the Lead Supplier (as the context requires).]
Supplier Contract Manager: the Supplier's principal point(s) of contact for managing this Agreement on behalf of the Supplier appointed under clause 14.

Supplier Equipment: any equipment, including hardware, tools, systems, cabling or devices, used by the Supplier or its subcontractors in the supply of the Services, including any items specified in a Statement of Work but excluding any items which are hired or loaned from the Customer.
Supplier Group Members: the Supplier and its Affiliates, and Supplier Group Member means any of them.

[Supplier Materials: all documents, information[, software], items and other materials in any form which are or have been developed independently of this Agreement by the Supplier or its suppliers or licensors and are included in the Deliverables.]

Supplier Personnel: all employees, workers, agents, consultants, contractors and other representatives of the Supplier, or any of its subcontractors, who are engaged in the performance of this Agreement from time to time, and Supplier Person means any of them.
[Systems: the information and communications technology systems of a party, including its software, equipment, and databases.]
Term: means the term of this Agreement.

Termination Assistance Period: the period starting on the earlier of [six] months before the expiry of this Agreement or the date of notice of termination of this Agreement by either party and ending [three] months after expiry or termination.
[Territory: [[COUNTRY] OR the country where the Customer is based].]

[Third Party Materials: all documents, information[, software], items and other materials in any form belonging to a third party [(other than an Affiliate of either party)] which the Supplier uses or wants to use in connection with the Services [and which are only made commercially available on standard terms that are not typically negotiated].]
UK GDPR: has the meaning given in section 3(10) (as supplemented by section 205(4)) of the Data Protection Act 2018.
VAT: value added tax [or any equivalent tax] chargeable in the UK [or elsewhere].
A person includes a natural person, corporate or unincorporated body (whether or not having separate legal personality).
A reference to a company includes any company, corporation or other body corporate, wherever and however incorporated or established.
Unless the context otherwise requires, words in the singular include the plural and in the plural include the singular.
[Unless expressly provided otherwise in this Agreement, a OR A] reference to legislation or a legislative provision:
is a reference to it as [amended, extended or re-enacted from time to time OR it is in force as at the Effective Date]; and
includes all subordinate legislation made [from time to time OR as at the Effective Date] under that legislation or legislative provision.
A reference to writing or written excludes fax but not email.
Any obligation on a party not to do something includes an obligation not to allow that thing to be done.

Any words following the terms including, include, in particular, for example or any similar expression will be interpreted as illustrative and will not limit the sense of the words preceding those terms.
Term

The MSA [starts on OR is deemed to have started on] the [MSA] Effective Date and continues, unless terminated earlier in accordance with clause 24, until [[DATE] OR the [NUMBER] anniversary of the [MSA] Effective Date] when it terminates automatically without notice.
[Adoption Agreements
The MSA establishes a framework for the supply of services by Supplier Group Members to Customer Group Members.

If a Customer Group Member wishes to receive any services under the MSA from a Supplier Group Member, it will first enter into an Adoption Agreement with the Supplier Group Member that creates a contractual relationship between them. The parties to an Adoption Agreement may then enter into Statements of Work setting out the Services to be provided. The Lead Customer and Lead Supplier, as parties to the MSA, do not need to enter into an Adoption Agreement before agreeing Statements of Work between themselves.
Each Adoption Agreement constitutes a separate agreement to the MSA that incorporates its terms except as amended in the Adoption Agreement.

Each party will, and will procure that its Affiliates will, not seek to amend the MSA as its terms are incorporated into an Adoption Agreement other than for legal or regulatory reasons [or to reflect local business practice]. The terms of an Adoption Agreement will take precedence over the terms of the MSA in the event of any inconsistency.

Each party to an Adoption Agreement may only enforce its rights under that Adoption Agreement against the other party to it. Neither the Lead Supplier, Lead Customer nor any of their Affiliates will have any liability under an Adoption Agreement unless party to it.]
Statements of Work
The Customer and the Supplier may, from time to time, enter into Statements of Work. Each Statement of Work will refer to and be subject to the terms of this Agreement.

[In drafting a Statement of Work, the parties will calculate the Charges by reference to the agreed rates for specific services set out in Schedule 4. [This clause 4.2 will cease to apply if the Customer fails to comply with clause 5.1.]]

Each Statement of Work forms part of this Agreement and is not a separate contract. The terms of a Statement of Work only apply to the Services performed under that Statement of Work and not to Services performed under any other Statement of Work.

If there is an inconsistency between any of the provisions of this Agreement and the provisions of any Statement of Work, the provisions of this Agreement will prevail [(unless the parties expressly state otherwise in the "Special Terms" section of a Statement of Work)].
[Non-]Exclusivity

[This Agreement is not an exclusive arrangement. The Customer may purchase services that are similar or identical to the Services from any third party or provide them itself. [The Supplier may supply services that are similar or identical to the Services to any third party.]
OR

[To maintain the pricing set out in Schedule 4, the OR The] Customer will[, and will procure that each Customer Group Member will,] purchase all of its requirements in [TERRITORY WHERE THE SUPPLIER IS GRANTED EXCLUSIVITY] for [SERVICES TO BE SUPPLIED EXCLUSIVELY] only from the Supplier or any person(s) designated in writing by the Supplier. [The obligations in this clause 5.1 are subject to the exceptions in clause 5.2.]

[If the Supplier is unable to meet the Customer's requirements [for any reason OR because of a lack of capacity or due to an event beyond its reasonable control], the Customer may purchase the services that the Supplier is unable to provide from any third party.]
Supplier responsibilities
The Supplier will:
provide the Services and Deliverables in accordance with the terms and conditions of this Agreement [in all material respects];

ensure that the Services and Deliverables conform [in all material respects] to the specifications, requirements and standards set out in the Statement of Work [and that the Deliverables are fit for any purpose expressly or implicitly made known to the Supplier by the Customer];

perform the Services with [the highest level of care, skill and diligence in accordance with best practice in the Supplier's industry, profession or trade OR the care, skill and diligence expected from a supplier [highly OR reasonably and suitably] skilled and experienced in providing services similar to the Services OR reasonable care and skill in accordance with generally recognised standards in the Supplier's industry, profession or trade];

[ensure that the Deliverables, and all goods, materials, standards and techniques used in providing the Services, are of the [best quality OR standard expected of a skilled and experienced provider of services similar to the Services] and are free from defects in workmanship, installation and design [in all material respects];]
[co-operate with the Customer in all matters relating to the Services and comply with the Customer's [reasonable] instructions [as to the performance of the Services];]
[provide the Customer with information, advice and training as reasonably required by the Customer to make effective use of the Services;]

obtain and maintain all licences, consents and permissions needed to supply the Services in accordance with this Agreement [(excluding any licences, consents and permissions that the Customer is expressly responsible for obtaining or maintaining under this Agreement [or should reasonably be responsible for obtaining and maintaining])];

[[take reasonable steps to] keep Customer Equipment safe and secure while in the possession or control of the Supplier. [Subject to this, the Customer Equipment remains at the sole risk and responsibility of the Customer][; and OR .]]
[[ANY OTHER GENERAL OBLIGATIONS].]

[If the Customer obtains any services from a third party that have an interrelationship with the Services, the Supplier will use [all] reasonable endeavours to co-operate with the third party to ensure that the provision of the Services and the third party's services are provided with a minimum of disruption to the Customer's business.]

[The Supplier will inform the Customer Contract Manager in writing on completion of each [Deliverable [or [OTHER PART OF THE SERVICES]] (each a Work Item). The Customer will review the Work Item to determine if it conforms [in all material respects] to the requirements of this Agreement, including any specifications or acceptance criteria set out in the Statement of Work, and provide the Supplier Contract Manager with written approval of the Work Item or a written statement of defects to be corrected. ]

[The Customer will not unreasonably withhold or delay its acceptance of a Work Item. [If the Customer puts any Work Item into commercial use or does not inform the Supplier Contract Manager in writing of any errors within [NUMBER] Business Days of being informed that the Work Item is complete under clause 6.3, the Work Item is deemed to be approved by the Customer. If the Customer approves the Work Item with minor errors, the Supplier will fix those minor errors promptly [and in any event in accordance with any timescales reasonably specified by the Customer]. ]

[If the Customer provides a written statement of errors, the Supplier will correct the errors in the Work Item at no additional cost to the Customer. The Supplier will do so within [25]% of the duration of the original timeframe for provision of the Work Item or, if longer, within [five] Business Days after receiving the Customer's statement of errors (Deadline), and inform the Customer Contract Manager in writing when the corrections are complete. The approval process in clause 6.3 and clause 6.4 will then be repeated. If the Supplier fails to correct the errors by the Deadline, the Customer may (without prejudice to any other rights or remedies it may have):
require the Supplier to repeat the process to correct errors in this clause 6.5;

approve the Work Item subject to [a reasonable deduction from the Charges to reflect the errors in the Work Item and the delays caused by the Work Item not being compliant when first completed OR any conditions that the Customer reasonably determines [provided that the conditions may not, without the Supplier's prior written consent, increase its obligations or restrict its rights or remedies under this Agreement]; and
finally refuse to approve the Work Item and refuse any subsequent performance which the Supplier attempts to make.]
[If the Customer finally refuses to approve a Work Item under clause 6.5(c), it may (without prejudice to any other rights or remedies it may have) do one or more of the following:
refuse to pay for the Work Item and require the Supplier to refund [immediately] any sums previously paid to the Supplier for that Work Item; and
purchase substitute services or deliverables elsewhere [and reclaim from the Supplier any additional costs it incurs].]

[The Supplier will perform the Services and deliver the Deliverables in accordance with the Performance Dates. If the Supplier fails to meet any Performance Date, then (without prejudice to any other rights or remedies that the Customer may have):

the Supplier will, until the Customer exercises its rights under clause 6.7(d)(i), take all additional steps necessary to perform the Services and deliver the Deliverables as soon as possible after the missed Performance Date and at no additional cost to the Customer;
the Customer may withhold payment for the delayed Services or Deliverables until the Supplier remedies the delay; [and]
[the Supplier will pay the Customer any delay payments specified in the Statement of Work in accordance with clause 6.8; and]

if the Performance Date is specified as "key" in the Statement of Work, or the Supplier fails to complete the Services or Deliverables within [five] Business Days of the missed Performance Date, the Customer may:
refuse to accept any subsequent performance of the delayed Services or supply of the delayed Deliverables which the Supplier attempts to make;
purchase substitute services or deliverables from elsewhere [and reclaim from the Supplier any additional costs it incurs]; and
require the Supplier to refund [immediately] any sums previously paid by the Customer in respect of the delayed Services or Deliverables.
OR
The Supplier will perform the Services in a timely and professional manner. The Supplier will use [best OR reasonable] endeavours to meet any Performance Dates [but these dates are estimates only].]

[The Supplier will pay the delay payments under clause 6.7(c) on demand or the Customer may deduct them from its payments to the Supplier. The delay payments will start to accrue on the day after the missed Performance Date and continue to accrue until:
the Supplier completes the performance of the delayed Services or delivers the delayed Deliverables;
the Customer exercises its rights under clause 6.7(d)(i) or terminates this Agreement;
the accrued delay payments equal the maximum sum set out in the Statement of Work; or
this Agreement expires,
whichever is earlier. The parties confirm that these delay payments are reasonable and proportionate to protect the Customer's legitimate interest in timely performance.]
[Service Levels
The Supplier will meet or exceed all Service Levels in its provision of the Services.
The Supplier will:
monitor and report on its performance against the Service Levels in accordance with the requirements set out in the Statement of Work;
maintain adequate technical and organisational procedures [and auditable tools] to enable it to monitor and report on its performance against the Service Levels; and
provide full access to the Customer to all reports on performance against the Service Levels and to the metrics and underlying data used to assess its performance.
If the Supplier fails to meet a Service Level, it will:
take immediate steps to minimise the impact of the failure and correct any fault or defect in its systems, materials or processes which gave rise to the failure;
promptly investigate the failure and provide the Customer with a written report identifying its causes and consequences and the steps the Supplier will take to ensure the failure is not repeated; and

apply any Service Credits due to the Customer against the Supplier's next invoice. If there is no next invoice, the Customer may issue an invoice for the relevant amount to the Supplier which the Supplier will pay within [NUMBER] days of its receipt.

The parties agree that Service Credits reflect the Customer's legitimate interest in avoiding a failure to meet a Service Level because of the adverse impact it would have on its business operations. [The Customer's right to receive Service Credits is in addition to its right to pursue any other remedy it may have. Any damages for which the Supplier may be liable to the Customer in respect of the same cause of action that gave rise to the Service Credits will be deemed to include (and the Supplier's liability will be reduced by) the amount of the Service Credits already paid or credited by the Supplier OR Service Credits are the Customer's sole financial remedy for the Supplier's failure to achieve the Service Levels.]]
Supplier Personnel
The Supplier will ensure that the Supplier Personnel:
are suitably skilled and experienced to perform the tasks assigned to them [and have been adequately trained in the provision of the Services]; [and]

[have all licences, permits, visas and consents required for the proper performance of this Agreement, including the right to work in all relevant jurisdictions, and have been properly screened and vetted by the Supplier to ensure they are fit for the positions that they are in; and]
are in sufficient number to enable the Supplier to fulfil its obligations under this Agreement.

[If the Customer (acting reasonably) believes that any Supplier Person is not performing the Services properly or effectively or is disruptive to the Customer's business, the Customer may require the Supplier to remove that Supplier Person from the Customer's account and ensure they cease to be involved in the Services. The Supplier will do so at its cost and [will use reasonable endeavours to minimise disruption OR without material interruption] to the Services.]

[If any Supplier Personnel will be working at any Customer Group Member's premises, the Supplier will [use reasonable endeavours to] ensure that those Supplier Personnel observe all reasonable health and safety rules and security requirements that are in force at those premises and have been communicated to the Supplier in writing in advance. [The Customer may require the immediate removal of any Supplier Person from the premises who is in breach of any of these rules and requirements and the Supplier will comply with that requirement without [material] interruption to the performance of the Services OR The Supplier will not be liable if it is unable to perform any of its obligations in accordance with this Agreement as a result of observing these rules and requirements].]

The Supplier will ensure that the Supplier Personnel do not act or appear to act as representatives or agents of any Customer Group Member [unless expressly authorised to do so in writing by the Customer].
[The Supplier will:

use the Key Personnel in the provision of the Services [and procure that the Key Personnel spend the percentage of their working hours set out in the Statement of Work in the provision of the Services].

promptly inform the Customer of the absence (or the anticipated absence) of any of the Key Personnel [(other than for short-term absences of [two] weeks or less)] and, if required by the Customer, ensure suitably qualified temporary cover for that individual is in place.
[not remove or replace OR use [best OR reasonable] endeavours not to make changes to] any of the Key Personnel, provided that the Supplier may do so if:
requested to do so by the Customer under clause 8.2;
the person is on maternity leave, paternity leave, shared parental leave, or long-term sick leave;
the person is suspended for misconduct;
the element of the Services in respect of which the individual was engaged has been completed [to the Customer's reasonable satisfaction];
the person resigns from their employment with the Supplier or ceases to be employed by the Supplier; or
the Supplier obtains the prior written consent of the Customer (not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed).

[obtain the prior [written] approval of the Customer [(approval not to be unreasonably withheld or delayed)] to any replacement for a Key Personnel member OR ensure that any replacement for a Key Personnel member has the qualifications and experience to carry out the tasks assigned to the Key Personnel member being replaced];
[use reasonable endeavours to] ensure that the role of each of its Key Personnel is not vacant (in terms of a permanent representative) for more than [ten] Business Days; and

bear all costs and expenses associated with any appointment, removal, or replacement of Key Personnel, including time spent by any replacement familiarising themselves with the Supplier's obligations under this Agreement.]
[Each party will comply with its obligations in Schedule 5.]
Customer responsibilities
The Customer will:
co-operate with the Supplier in all matters relating to the Services [and ensure that its other suppliers co-operate with the Supplier where reasonably necessary];
[respond promptly to any reasonable requests from the Supplier for instructions or approvals required to provide the Services;]
provide access to the Customer's premises and other facilities as reasonably required by the Supplier[, and agreed with the Customer [in writing] in advance,] for the performance of the Services;

provide to the Supplier the information and materials specified in the Statement of Work [and all other information and materials reasonably required by the Supplier to provide the Services and ensure that they are accurate and complete [in all material respects]]; [and]
[provide any Customer Equipment specified in the Statement of Work by the dates and in the manner prescribed in that Statement of Work;]

[ensure that the Customer Equipment is in good working order [and suitable for the purposes for which it is used in relation to the Services] and conforms to all relevant legal standards or requirements;]

[maintain any Supplier Equipment in the Customer's possession or control [in good condition OR in accordance with the Supplier's instructions set out in the Statement of Work] and not dispose of or use the Supplier Equipment other than in accordance with the Supplier's written instructions or authorisation; and]

obtain and maintain all licences, consents and permissions that [relate specifically to the Customer's business and] are necessary to enable the Supplier to provide the Services[, including all licences, consents and permissions stated as being the Customer's responsibility in the Statement of Work].
[The Supplier will not be liable for any Losses incurred by the Customer as a result of using draft Deliverables as finished work [without the Supplier's prior written approval].]

To the extent that the Supplier's performance of its obligations under this Agreement is [directly] prevented or delayed by any [act or omission of the Customer (or any of its agents, consultants or other suppliers) OR breach by the Customer of [any of its obligations under this Agreement OR clause 9.1]] (Excusing Cause), the Supplier will not be in breach of this Agreement [provided the Supplier:
promptly notifies the Customer in writing [and in reasonable detail] of the alleged Excusing Cause and its impact on the ability of the Supplier to perform its obligations under this Agreement; and
uses [all] reasonable endeavours to perform its obligations notwithstanding the Excusing Cause].
[Without prejudice to any other right or remedy it may have, the Supplier will be:
allowed an extension of time to perform its obligations equal to the delay caused by the Excusing Cause; and

entitled to recover any Losses incurred as a result of the Excusing Cause, including [Charges unpaid due to its performance being prevented or delayed and] reasonable, additional costs incurred as a result of complying with clause 9.3(b) [if the Customer has approved these in advance].]
Non-solicitation
During the Term and for a period of [six] months after termination or expiry of this Agreement, each party agrees not to [(and to procure that its Affiliates do not)]:

solicit or entice away (or attempt to solicit or entice away) any Restricted Person from the employment or service of the other party [(or any of its Affiliates)], other than by means of a public recruitment campaign open to all-comers and not specifically targeted at the staff of the other party [or any of its Affiliates][; or
employ or engage any Restricted Person],

without the prior written consent of the other party. Restricted Person means any person employed or engaged by the other party [or any of its Affiliates] [at the level of [POSITION] or above] who is or has been involved in the provision or receipt of the Services or the management of this Agreement.

[If either party commits a breach of clause 10.1, that party will, on demand, pay to the other party a sum equal to [[PERCENTAGE]% of] one year's basic salary, or [[PERCENTAGE]% of] the annual fee, that was payable by the other party [(or its Affiliate)] to the Restricted Person, plus the recruitment costs incurred in replacing that person.]
Charges and payment
In consideration of the provision of the Services by the Supplier, the Customer will pay the Charges.
Where the Charges are calculated on a time and materials basis:
the Supplier's fee rates are as set out in the Statement of Work;

daily fee rates are calculated on the basis of an [eight]-hour day, worked during Business Hours.
